oc:kn_228493b2 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When updating state based on current state value, especially inside useCallback or async operations" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use functional setState updates (setItems(curr => [...curr, newItem])) instead of referencing state variables directly in callbacks. This produces stable callback references and prevents stale closures." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Functional updates eliminate the most common React closure bug — stale state references in callbacks. They also remove the need for state in dependency arrays, producing stable callback references that don't cause child re-renders." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_4e5b18b1 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing React Server Components or SSR code that handles per-request data like current user" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use mutable module-level variables to store request-scoped data in Server Components. Servers render concurrently in the same process, causing cross-request data leaks and race conditions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Module scope on the server is process-wide shared memory, not request-local state. Concurrent requests can overwrite each other's data, causing security bugs where one user sees another user's data." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_514481e7 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any async code in React components, API routes, or Server Actions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use sequential await for independent async operations. Always use Promise.all() to execute independent operations concurrently, and start promises immediately (don't await until the result is needed)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Sequential awaits create waterfalls — the #1 performance killer. Each sequential await adds full network latency, yielding 2-10× slowdowns. This is the highest-impact optimization category." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_631eff47 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing React component code, especially when parent variables need to be accessed" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never define components inside other components. This creates a new component type on every render, causing React to fully remount the child — destroying all state, DOM nodes, and re-running effects." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inline component definitions cause remounting on every parent render. Symptoms include input fields losing focus, animations restarting, and effects re-running unexpectedly. Always pass props instead." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_747af9c7 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When using React.cache() for per-request deduplication on the server" ;
    oc:directiveContent "React.cache() uses shallow equality (Object.is) for cache keys. Never pass inline objects as arguments to cached functions — each call creates a new reference, preventing cache hits." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inline objects like getUser({ uid: 1 }) create new references each call, so React.cache() never hits. Store the object in a variable and pass the same reference to get cache hits." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_88cd20cb a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing Next.js Server Actions (functions with 'use server')" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always authenticate and authorize inside each Server Action. Server Actions are public endpoints callable directly — do not rely on middleware, layout guards, or page-level checks." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Server Actions are exposed as public HTTP endpoints. Without internal auth checks, anyone can invoke mutations like deleteUser directly, bypassing page-level protections." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_aa9e88e0 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When passing props from React Server Components to Client Components" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Only pass the fields the client actually uses across RSC boundaries. The Server/Client boundary serializes all object properties into the HTML response, directly impacting page weight." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Serializing unnecessary fields (e.g., 50 fields when only 1 is used) bloats the HTML payload and slows page load. Minimize the data crossing the serialization boundary." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f7522cd6 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When reviewing or refactoring an existing React/Next.js codebase for performance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Apply rules by priority: first eliminate waterfalls and optimize bundle size (CRITICAL), then server-side performance (HIGH), then re-render optimization (MEDIUM), then JavaScript micro-optimizations (LOW). Focus on the highest-impact changes first." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The 8 categories are ordered by measurable impact. Waterfall elimination yields 2-10× improvements. Bundle optimization reduces 200-800ms import costs. Lower categories provide incremental gains that compound but are less impactful individually." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

